<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;Responses&nbsp;(Collapsed&nbsp;for&nbsp;size)</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">-&nbsp;Close</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p>1) Agreed, will not add an interview log, but may add excerpts from the Parawatch forums to develop the story and Parawatches mindset.</p>
<p>2) Looking at the photo does nothing, but copying it does, creating a non-anomalous frog of the same type as the anomaly within the vicinity of the person who copied the photo. While this may not <em>immediately</em> be recognized anomalous it would some become apparent after a bit of experimenting. After the first Parawatch member discovered its' properties they sent the relevant instructions with the picture.</p>
<p>3)</p>
<blockquote>
<p><em>Depending on your headcanon, the foundation has AI that sweep the internet for images all the time… why couldn't one of those merely delete the image as soon as its sent up?</em></p>
</blockquote>
<p>Because, as you said, the photo isn't instantly recognizable as anomalous, and I doubt that the Foundation copies every Parawatch page for review. Additionally, it's my head cannon that Parawatch members take pictures of and post about weird animals all the time. After the Foundation picks up on the anomaly, taking it down won't do any good as many Parawatch members have recognized it as anomalous and stored it in their computers, continually re-posting it and spreading it through non-Parawatch channels.</p>
<blockquote>
<p><em>Additionally I think it might make more sense to get some of the mods on the parawatch wiki to be double agents, and then they could call these things as off limits for members</em>.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Maybe they do and maybe they tried. But the Parawatch members would just create new threads and posts to replace the ones banned or deleted by the mods, especially if they were certain the anomaly was real. And if by 'these things' you mean actual, demonstrable, online anomalous phenomena that the rest of Parawatch already know about I feel that the other Parawatchs would catch on very quickly that the mods were double-agents.</p>
<blockquote>
<p><em>This could also introduce a meaty sub story about the Foundation trying to interfere directly with the Parawatch community which hasn't been done much before.</em></p>
</blockquote>
<p>The entire concept of this article is the Foundation interfering with the Parawatch community in order to stop a breach of the veil. The Foundation frequently deletes posts and erases the memories of members, but never at this scale and never this directly. Some of the Parawatch forum excerpts will probably feature Foundation agents posing as members and trying to dismiss it as a hoax.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Also… I don't see the comedy, because you haven't really explained. It just sounds like someone sharing pics of a frog.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>I find the concept of the Foundation almost being defeated and the veil shattered by Parawatch and a frog rather humorous. That being said, the article isn't primarily Comedy so I have changed 'Comedy' to 'Minor Comedy' in the Genre section.</p>
</div>
</div>
