<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">[+]&nbsp;Open&nbsp;for&nbsp;crit</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">–&nbsp;hide&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p>Perhaps a minor concern but this feels&#8230;like it goes a bit against the Parawatch writing guide by like, explicitly giving them an anomaly and letting them fully understand what it does. In general, the parawatch vibe is more 'paranoid conspiracy theorists who have no idea what's really going on', and this feels&#8230;like it doesn't quite capture that?</p>
<p>I'm also kinda uncertain about this specifically as a SCP article: it feels&#8230;kinda like a lot of the fun would be easier to convey if this was a parawatch format where you could open with the post describing how to replicate the anomaly and then have the breathless excitement of them replicating it and having confirmation into like, the paranoia as folk deny it and like the foundation start to shut it down and stuff? Like, obviously you can convey this in a SCP article by including parawatch forum posts but at some point, it'll feel&#8230;excessive and like it's unnecessary to include this many; and my concern is that it's very possible it'll feel that way as soon as you include any parawatch posts.</p>
<p>I can't quite put my finger on why but it also just kinda feels like the narrative progression here feels&#8230;very generic? Like, it's not <em>exactly</em> the same as a generic containment breach story but it feels like it shares enough in common that it feels like one; the angle of the Foundation shutting down Parawatch feels interesting but it feels like this is framed in a way where we can't really see the weight of that decision because we're seeing stuff from the Foundation's POV.</p>
<p>I guess really it does just come down to me looking at this and thinking it'd feel much better if it was written in the same kinda style as <a href="/this-is-how-we-build-revelation">This Is How We Build Revelation</a>, where you blend the prose tale material from the PoV of someone on Parawatch with the forum posts they make, and the responses they get; since all the interesting stuff is happening on the Parawatch side of the story, not the Foundation side.</p>
<p>Also a few minor things:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>A simple anomaly is discovered by WWS.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Why WWS? It's such a brief mention that it feels like this is just being done to explain why the Foundation aren't more on the ball here; except the tight relationship between WWS and the Foundation means it still kinda feels weird how little the Foundation know going in; and it also feels&#8230;weirdly irrelevant.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>The main story of the article comes when a member of the Parawatch community gets their hands on one of the photos and discovers it's anomalous properties.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>How do they get their hands on one of the photos?</p>
<blockquote>
<p>The article closes out with a note regarding the difficulty of maintaining the veil in the internet age and about being thankful the image wasn't memetic.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>This feels too much like it just kinda summarises things we've already seen in the article? Like, you're showing us the difficulty of maintaining the veil; so telling us afterwards feels&#8230;unnecessary?</p>
</div>
</div>
