<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">[+]&nbsp;Open&nbsp;for&nbsp;crit</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">–&nbsp;hide&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<blockquote>
<p>however the member believes that all anomalies should be known to the public, which is why they joined Parawatch.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>This motivation feels a lot more Serpents Hand-y than it does Parawatch-y; I don't think this is a huge concern but it might be worth thinking about.</p>
<p>My core concern is that this still feels extremely focussed on the Parawatch poster: I don't think this is necessarily a bad idea but it feels like everything is being driven by what they do and how they feel about the situation and it feels to me like this will be really hard for you to convey via the framing of a SCP article, where you can't like, directly get into their head or anything.</p>
<p>My other concern is there's a feeling of this lacking stakes: like it's obviously bad if Parawatch has all this information, and the foundation trying to shut down parawatch isn't a bad response or anything; but it feels like there's not really a sense of 'if parawatch does x, y will happen; so we have to prevent x'. On the flip side, there's not really a sense of the Foundation's actions having consequences either: like, if the Foundation does shut this down, what happens?</p>
<p>Iunno, really what I'm getting at is there's a lot of this I kinda like but it feels like it's missing something to just, really get it to work and I'm not quite sure <em>what</em> it is. It might be just some emotional framing: like, who are we rooting for here? What point are you making about releasing information about all anomalies to the public?</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>

