			<div class="content" id="post-content-4865537">
									

<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;Responses</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">-&nbsp;Close</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<blockquote>
<p>This motivation feels a lot more Serpents Hand-y than it does Parawatch-y; I don't think this is a huge concern but it might be worth thinking about.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Parawatch members have a wide variety of motivations for being members of the wiki. Some of those motivations happen to align with the Serpents Hand, attempting to speak openly about anomalies, even if they don't have any idea what's going on.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>My core concern is that this still feels extremely focused on the Parawatch poster: I don't think this is necessarily a bad idea but it feels like everything is being driven by what they do and how they feel about the situation and it feels to me like this will be really hard for you to convey via the framing of a SCP article, where you can't like, directly get into their head or anything.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Perhaps I was a bit unclear what I meant by 'Excerpts from Parawatch forums' in the page layout section. While the article will <em>start</em> as a SCP article there will be a link at the bottom of the page, with a title like &quot;View ongoing containment measures&quot;. This will lead to a page filled with many Parawatch forum threads. It's through these threads that the story will be told and they will allow incite into the motivations and feelings of the poster. There will also be, as stated, an interview.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>My other concern is there's a feeling of this lacking stakes: like it's obviously bad if Parawatch has all this information, and the foundation trying to shut down parawatch isn't a bad response or anything; but it feels like there's not really a sense of 'if parawatch does x, y will happen; so we have to prevent x'. On the flip side, there's not really a sense of the Foundation's actions having consequences either: like, if the Foundation does shut this down, what happens?</p>
</blockquote>
<p>I feel that you missed the purpose of the revision. I have now changed the concept from &quot;Parawatch makes a mass-movement to expose an anomaly to the public&quot; to &quot;A standard Foundation cover-up focusing on Parawatch and their responses&quot;. It is no longer a high-stakes situation, nor-with long reaching consequences. The Foundatiion is no longer trying to 'shut down' Parawatch, rather they are interfering with a single anomaly on the wiki which is proving more difficult than usual. This article is now mainly focused on Parawatch responding to the situation along with the reactions of one truth-seeker in particular and their interactions with each other and the Foundation are the story. Their are no stakes because the Foundation was always going to succeed somehow, but Parawatch doesn't no that and just keeps trying.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Iunno, really what I'm getting at is there's a lot of this I kinda like but it feels like it's missing something to just, really get it to work and I'm not quite sure what it is. It might be just some emotional framing: like, who are we rooting for here? What point are you making about releasing information about all anomalies to the public?</p>
</blockquote>
<p>I am trying to get the readers to root for the Underdog, in this case Parawatch and that particular poster, despite knowing that they won't succeed. I also want to invoke feelings of sympathy for someone who has discovered and is exited about an anomaly, but is being shut down by the Foundation. As for releasing anomalies to the public, that isn't really a major theme to the article other than part of the poster's motivation to not be stopped and the reason they decline a Foundation position. However, if it was a part I suppose the message would be that the public may want and accept knowledge about the anomalous, but the Foundation won't let that happen because <em>they</em> believe the public isn't ready for it.</p>
</div>
</div>
